[04:58.02]	A gallant prize? ha, cousin, is it not?
[05:00.57]WESTMORELAND	In faith,
[05:01.49]	It is a conquest for a prince to boast of.
[05:04.40]KING HENRY IV	Yea, there thou makest me sad and makest me sin
[05:07.62]	In envy that my Lord Northumberland
[05:10.17]	Should be the father to so blest a son,
[05:12.91]	A son who is the theme of honour's tongue;
[05:15.82]	Amongst a grove, the very straightest plant;
[05:18.80]	Who is sweet Fortune's minion and her pride:
[05:21.83]	Whilst I, by looking on the praise of him,
[05:24.69]	See riot and dishonour stain the brow
[05:27.36]	Of my young Harry. O that it could be proved
[05:30.40]	That some night-tripping fairy had exchanged
[05:33.50]	In cradle-clothes our children where they lay,
[05:36.66]	And call'd mine Percy, his Plantagenet!
[05:39.33]	Then would I have his Harry, and he mine.
[05:42.12]	But let him from my thoughts. What think you, coz,
[05:45.40]	Of this young Percy's pride? the prisoners,
[05:48.32]	Which he in this adventure hath surprised,
[05:51.24]	To his own use he keeps; and sends me word,
[05:54.15]	I shall have none but Mordake Earl of Fife.
[05:57.13]WESTMORELAND	This is his uncle's teaching; this is Worcester,
[06:00.35]	Malevolent to you in all aspects;
[06:02.72]	Which makes him prune himself, and bristle up
[06:05.81]	The crest of youth against your dignity.
[06:08.61]KING HENRY IV	But I have sent for him to answer this;
